the Day of Arrival of One Million Refugees / rHentschke, Felicitas -- tSection 7: Being at Home in the World: Thinking with Houses and Homes -- tMaking Home on the High Seas: Bulgarian Seafarers between Ship and Shore / rKremakova, Milena -- tOwning a Home in Bamako: To Be at Home after Death / rDougnon, Isaie -- tFrom Ancestral Tablets to Patriotic Portraits: Remembering Kinship in Rural Chinese Homes / rBruckermann, Charlotte -- tUnhomely Afterlives: The Works and Lives of Rabindranath Tagore / rPinheiro, Cláudio -- tReflections I -- tServant Testimonies and Anglo-Indian Homes in Nineteenth-Century India / rVarma, Nitin -- tReflections II -- tOn Homes, Work, and Personhood: An Interview with Prabhu Mohapatra / rMohapatra, Prabhu / Hentschke, Felicitas / Varma, Nitin -- tOn Photography and History: An Interview with Alf Lüdtke / rLüdtke, Alf / Hentschke, Felicitas / Williams, James -- tReflections III -- tWhy Homes Still Matter: Thoughts on Mamphela Ramphele's A Bed Called Home / rFourchard, Laurent -- tContributor Biographies -- tPicture Credits -- tIndex  aHouses and homes are dynamic spaces within which people work to organize and secure their lives, livelihoods and relationships. Written by a team of renowned historians and anthropologists, and and accompanied by original photography by Maurice Weiss, To Be at Home: House,Work, and Self in the Modern World compares the ways people in different societies and historical periods strive to make and keep houses and homes under conditions of change, upheaval, displacement, impoverishment and violence. These conditions speak to the challenges of life in our modern world. The contributors of this volume position the home as a new nodal point between work, the self and the world to explore people's creativity, agency and labour. Houses and homes prove complex and powerful concepts - if also often elusive - invoking places, persons, objects, emotions, values, attachments and fantasies. This book demonstrates how the relations between houses, work and the self have transformed dramatically and unpredictably under conditions of capitalism and modernity - and continue to change today.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Sep 2018)1 aHentschke, Felicitas, eeditor.1 aWilliams, James, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018 Englishz978311060403008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018z9783110603149oZDB-23-DEG0 cEPUBz97831105801360 cprintz978311057987140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110582765423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110582765.jpg  a978-3-11-060403-0  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060425-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishb2018  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aZDB-23-DEGb2018  aZDB-23-DGGb2017